api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.Authoriz:
This header is added because of the authorization method used for this request.
The value of this header is tentative. You can find the exact value in the actual request once the request is sent.
Use the auth tab to remove authorization or to change the value of this header.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.Cache-Co:
{platform} added "Cache-Control: no-cache" as a precautionary measure to prevent the server from returning stale responses when one makes repeated requests.
You can remove this header in the app settings or enter a new one with a different value.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.Content-:
The Content-Type header is added to help the server identify the media type of the request body that is present in this request.
Use the request body tab to control the value or to remove this header.

The Content-Length header was added to indicate to the server the size of the request body that is added to this request. The server uses this value to parse the request body accurately.
You can remove the head or enter a new one with a different value.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.Cookie:
Existing cookies in the cookie jar will be added as headers for this request.
The value of this header is tentative. You can find the exact value in the actual request once the request is sent.
Use the cookies window to remove cookies or to change the value of this header.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.Host:
The Host header is added to identify the domain name for which a request is being sent to the server. This header is implicitly sent by every HTTP client.
You can remove the header or enter a new one with a different value. It is most likely that without this header, your request will return an HTTP 400 error.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.User-Age:
The User-Agent header is added to help the server identify {platform} as the HTTP requesting application or client.
It is recommended that this header be sent, but you can remove the header or enter a new one with a different value.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.Accept:
The "Accept: */*" header is added to tell the server that {platform} can understand and process all forms of response content types.
It is recommended that this header be sent, but you can remove the header or enter a new one with a different value.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.Accept-E:
The Accept-Encoding header is added to indicate to the server that {platform} HTTP client supports a defined list of content-encoding or compression algorithms as a response.
You can remove the header or enter a new one with a different value. Doing that may not accurately render the response within the app.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.http.Connecti:
The Connection header is added to indicate the server to keep the underlying network connection open once the current response is received. This allows {platform} to reuse the same connection for faster response times in subsequent requests to the same server.
You can remove this header or enter a new one with a different value, such as `Connection: close` to control this behavior.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.ws.Host: The Host request-header field specifies the Internet host and port number of the resource being requested, as obtained from the original URI.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.ws.Connection: The Connection header field allows the sender to specify options that are desired for that particular connection.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.ws.Upgrade: The WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
api.api.parameter.systemHeader.ws.Sec-WebSoc:
The Sec-WebSocket-Key header field is used in the WebSocket opening handshake. It is sent from the client to the server to provide part of the information used by the server to prove that it received a valid WebSocket opening handshake.
This helps ensure that the server does not accept connections from non-WebSocket clients (e.g., HTTP clients) that are being abused to send data to unsuspecting WebSocket servers.

The Sec-WebSocket-Version header field is used in the WebSocket opening handshake. It is sent from the client to the server to indicate the protocol version of the connection.
This enables servers to correctly interpret the opening handshake and subsequent data being sent from the data, and close the connection if the server cannot interpret that data in a safe manner.

The Sec-WebSocket-Extensions header field is used in the WebSocket opening handshake. It is initially sent from the client to the server, and then subsequently sent from the server to the client, to agree on a set of protocol-level extensions to use for the duration of the connection.
